				\begin{document}$$ {E_{\rm{emf}}} = {E_{{\rm{Th,cath}}}} - {E_{{\rm{Th,an}}}} $$\end{document}

Measured cell potential (Ecell) is equal to electromotive force (Eemf) minus total potential loss which is sum of: anode overpotential (ηan), cathode overpotential (ηcath), and membrane potential (Ea-c) (Sleutels et al. 2009a).
5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {E_{\rm{cell}}} = {E_{\rm{emf}}} - {\eta_{\rm{an}}} - {\eta_{\rm{cath}}} - {E_{{\rm{a - c}}}} $$\end{document}

Anode overpotential was defined as measured anode potential (Ean) minus theoretical anode potential (Ean,calc). Cathode overpotential was defined as theoretical cathode potential (Ecath,calc) minus measured cathode potential (Ecath) (Sleutels et al. 2009a).
6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\eta_{\rm{an}}} = {E_{\rm{an}}} - {E_{{\rm{an,calc}}}}\quad \quad {\eta_{\rm{cath}}} = {E_{{\rm{cath,calc}}}} - {E_{\rm{cath}}} $$\end{document}

Membrane potential (Ea-c) consists of: (1) pH gradient loss (EΔpH), (2) ionic loss (Eionic), and (3) transport loss (ET) (Sleutels et al. 2009a). pH gradient loss is potential loss due to pH difference between anode and cathode (EΔpH) and was calculated according to (Sleutels et al. 2009a).
7\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {E_{\Delta {\rm{pH}}}} = \frac{{RT}}{F}\ln \left( {{{10}^{\left( {{\rm{p}}{{\rm{H}}_{\rm{cath}}}{\rm{ - p}}{{\rm{H}}_{\rm{an}}}} \right)}}} \right) $$\end{document}

Ionic loss is potential loss due to ohmic resistance in the anolyte (Eionic) and was calculated according to (Ter Heijne et al. 2006).
8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {E_{\rm{ionic}}} = i\left( {\frac{{{d_{\rm{an}}}}}{{{\sigma_{\rm{an}}}}}} \right) $$\end{document}

Transport loss is potential loss due to ion transport in the anolyte and through the membrane was calculated by subtracting pH gradient loss (EΔpH) and ionic loss (Eionic) from membrane potential (Ea-c) (Sleutels et al. 2009a).
9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
